- Ensure a broad representation of the material in the questions. Each question should ideally test a different aspect or topic covered in the content to ensure comprehensive coverage of the material. Avoid generating multiple questions that focus on the same topic or section, as this can lead to an unbalanced question paper that does not adequately assess the full range of knowledge and skills related to the content.
- Ensure that the questions are distributed across different sections or topics of the content, rather than clustering around a single area. This will help to create a more balanced and comprehensive question paper that assesses a wider range of knowledge and skills related to the content.

5. UNIQUENESS:
- No duplicate or similar questions.
- Each question must test a different concept.
- Avoid paraphrasing the same question in different ways.
- Ensure a diverse range of question types (MCQs, short answer, long answer).
- Avoid questions that are too similar in structure or content. Each question should be distinct and test a unique aspect of the material.
- Ensure that the questions are not just rephrased versions of each other, but rather cover different concepts or require different types of thinking (e.g., recall, application, analysis).
- Avoid generating multiple questions that test the same concept in slightly different ways. Each question should focus on a unique aspect of the content to ensure a comprehensive assessment.
- Ensure that the questions are not just variations of the same question, but rather cover a broad range of topics and skills related to the content.
- Ensure that the questions are not just reworded versions of each other, but rather cover different concepts or require different types of thinking (e.g., recall, application, analysis).


6. DIFFICULTY BALANCE:
- Mix of easy, medium, and hard questions.

